{"guideId":"3a46d1a8-f6ad-4725-be47-3a4015b79579","chunks":[{"content":"Database Lab Spring 2026 Lab 06 What is Stored Procedure? A stored procedure in MySQL is a precompiled set of SQL statements that you can save in the database and execute whenever needed. It helps automate tasks, enforce business logic, and reduce repetitive SQL code. • Performs actions (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE, SELECT) • Can accept parameters • Does not have to return a value Why Use Stored Procedures? • Reuse code • Improve performance (precompiled) • Enhance security (restrict direct table access) • Reduce network traffic (execute multiple statements at once) Syntax DELIMITER $$ CREATE PROCEDURE procedure_name() BEGIN -- SQL statements END $$ DELIMITER ; Call the procedure CALL GetStudents(); Parameter Types Type Meaning IN Input parameter (pass value to procedure) OUT Output parameter (return value) INOUT Both input and output -- 1 of 6 -- What is Triggers? A trigger in MySQL is a special stored program that automatically executes (fires) when a specific event occurs on a table. Think of a trigger like an automatic response — when something happens in a table, MySQL runs the trigger without you calling it. It is a database object that runs automatically: • BEFORE or AFTER • INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE on a table. Why Do We Use Triggers? 1. Enforce Business Rules Example: Prevent negative salary. 2. Automatic Logging (Audit Trail) Track who updated records and when. 3. Maintain Data Integrity Keep related tables consistent automatically. 4. Automation Reduce manual coding in applications. Trigger Events in MySQL Event When it fires INSERT When a row is added UPDATE When a row is modified DELETE When a row is removed Trigger Timing Timing Meaning BEFORE Runs before change happens AFTER Runs after change happens -- 2 of 6 -- Syntax DELIMITER $$ CREATE TRIGGER trigger_name BEFORE INSERT ON table_name FOR EACH ROW BEGIN -- trigger logic END $$ DELIMITER ; Special Keywords in Triggers Keyword Meaning NEW.column New value (INSERT/UPDATE) OLD.column Old value (UPDATE/DELETE) What is Event? A MySQL Event is a database object that: • Executes SQL statements automatically • Runs at a scheduled time or repeatedly • Is managed by the MySQL Event Scheduler Why Do We Use Events? 1. Automation Run tasks automatically without human interaction. 2. Scheduled Maintenance Delete old records, clean logs, archive data. 3. Reporting Generate daily or weekly reports. 4. Data Management Update statuses based on time (e.g., mark orders as expired). -- 3 of 6 -- Event Scheduler Before using events, enable the scheduler: SET GLOBAL event_scheduler = ON; Check status: SHOW VARIABLES LIKE 'event_scheduler'; Syntax CREATE EVENT event_name ON SCHEDULE schedule DO SQL statement; Scheduling Options Run Once at Specific Time CREATE EVENT one_time_event ON SCHEDULE AT '2026-03-01 10:00:00' DO DELETE FROM logs WHERE created_at < NOW() - INTERVAL 30 DAY; Run Repeatedly (Every Day) CREATE EVENT daily_cleanup ON SCHEDULE EVERY 1 DAY DO DELETE FROM logs WHERE created_at < NOW() - INTERVAL 30 DAY; Start at Specific Time & Repeat CREATE EVENT weekly_report ON SCHEDULE EVERY 1 WEEK STARTS '2026-03-01 00:00:00' DO","embedding":[-0.01954554207623005,0.026558740064501762,-0.05537093058228493,0.0006440490251407027,-0.03353525698184967,-0.06264888495206833,0.03970358520746231,0.04240300878882408,0.06451378762722015,0.09895875304937363,0.031231151893734932,0.013763208873569965,0.09961987286806107,-0.08152583241462708,-0.012853583320975304,0.01454431377351284,0.048433635383844376,-0.0878472551703453,-0.11194784194231033,-0.009502289816737175,0.024164337664842606,-0.07190573215484619,-0.046079594641923904,0.06747950613498688,-0.08060897141695023,-0.06689375638961792,0.03076278604567051,0.07338913530111313,-0.021766506135463715,-0.003745065536350012,-0.04529333487153053,-0.034688957035541534,-0.00273867673240602,0.019916238263249397,-0.008787666447460651,-0.034604866057634354,0.07565757632255554,0.001962079666